snippet.textDisplay:
I hope this doesn't get me banned but my personal review of eBays purchase protection / insurance on cars: complete sham.
My story was about 12 years ago, but I bought a car, met the seller halfway (at night, on his request) - did a basic inspection after he showed up. Car seemed ok, completed payment and title transfer, drove 50 miles home, and went to bed thrilled I'd picked up my dream car - a couple 3000GT VR4. I started it the next morning and it was immediately obvious something was wrong: it sounded just like rod knock. I immediately contacted eBay who had me contact the seller who basically told me to screw off. I jumped through the hoops and then filled a claim while the car sat. After a few weeks eBay had me pay to tow the car to the Mitsubishi dealer and pay for an inspection. Just shy of $800 total. The dealership confirmed what I thought (rod knock) and also brought up they suspected (and eventually confirmed) the car had heavy weight oil in it to disguise the issue. They also discovered broken active aero, broken active steering, broken HVAC, and a number of other problems. I had the car towed home and waited for ebay to settle the claim - open and shut case I thought since in the interim the seller admitted on eBays communication system that he turned up the boost too high with an MBC and that "foreign cars were junk" and this one was "nothing but problems". eBay jerked me around for almost a WHOLE YEAR while I paid to insure the car and kept trying to contact them. Then the call came: claim denied. No real reason given but they suspected that somehow I'd done this in the 50 miles driven home that night. No reimbursement for the inspection they had me do. Just an extra heap of screwing me over on top of their claim. Don't put any weight in their purchase protection for even a second. Do as you normally would and do not remit payment until you have a car independently inspected.

snippet.textDisplay: Absolutely love this video. You look at things from the same perspective as I do, except you break it down much further with math and/or logic so the haters can't deny you are right! The only part I can't wrap my head around is that 10% increase in grip is the same as doubling the car's horsepower. I bought an NA MX-5 a few months ago and I love the car more than I thought I ever would! I have to agree with you on gearing as well. I have owned 3 sporty Mazda's and I absolutely love how they gear their cars. Where as with most other cars I've driven, the gearing is not ideal, but with Mazda's they hit the nail right on the head perfectly, allowing people to have more fun while driving within relatively legal limits. The only thing I would change on Miata's is the exhaust - it's much too quiet in stock form.

snippet.textDisplay:
Speaking of making cars lighter... I've recently been searching and now wondering ''why doesn't anyone make fiberglass hoods anymore?'' Back when I was much much younger, around 1999-2000 (yeah, the fiberglass bodykit rice rocket era😆), there were several fiberglass hoods, some w/ vents and others just plain oem style. I've had both fiberglass and carbon fiber hoods at separate times for my '97 H22 Prelude and they were both very similar in weight (ridiculously lighter than the factory, at least a few dozen lbs.) I think they'd be good for saving gas and slightly faster w/o affecting emissions. I know there are carbon fiber hoods but they're pretty pricey and they turn opaque yellowish w/ time. Fiberglass was always pretty inexpensive, but you gotta paint it. Hood pins/locks are needed as well, making your car look like a sleeper. People will asks ''what's under the hood''? Tell 'em, ''loser pops hood''. I miss being young.


Fun story: when i picked up my car after the shop installed/painted the FG hood, he asked me if I wanted to get hood locks/pins. I said, ''nah... I'll get it nxt time 😜''. So I got my car n drove away. I got on the freeway and... OH SHAT! My hood was flapping like a sail on a boat. Immediately got off the freeway n went back, ''yeah I'll get those pins'', lol. I gotta admit those pins make the car look sick.
snippet.textOriginal:
Speaking of making cars lighter... I've recently been searching and now wondering ''why doesn't anyone make fiberglass hoods anymore?''  Back when I was much much younger, around 1999-2000 (yeah, the fiberglass bodykit rice rocket era😆), there were several fiberglass hoods, some w/ vents and others just plain oem style.  I've had both fiberglass and carbon fiber hoods at separate times for my '97 H22 Prelude and they were both very similar in weight (ridiculously lighter than the factory, at least a few dozen lbs.)  I think they'd be good for saving gas and slightly faster w/o affecting emissions.  I know there are carbon fiber hoods but they're pretty pricey and they turn opaque yellowish w/ time.  Fiberglass was always pretty inexpensive, but you gotta paint it.  Hood pins/locks are needed as well, making your car look like a sleeper.  People will asks ''what's under the hood''?  Tell 'em, ''loser pops hood''.  I miss being young.


Fun story:  when i picked up my car after the shop installed/painted the FG hood, he asked me if I wanted to get hood locks/pins.  I said, ''nah... I'll get it nxt time 😜''.  So I got my car n drove away.  I got on the freeway and... OH SHAT! My hood was flapping like a sail on a boat.  Immediately got off the freeway n went back, ''yeah I'll get those pins'', lol.  I gotta admit those pins make the car look sick.

snippet.textDisplay:
Affordable dream cars are always the best ones.
Welcome to the Mazda club! I myself have a first generation RX-7, and I absolutely love it. Really cheap, really fun, and a huge learning experience the whole time. Basically everything I know about cars has stemmed from fixing and maintaining my FB. Good luck on your exploits with the new Miata!

Also side note: Its very interesting how your new Miata actually weighs less than the FB RX-7. The USDM S2 version of the FB weighs 2360 lbs. Back in 1983, my car would have been making 100hp at about 6800rpm and roughly 107 lb-ft at roughly 4500rpm. The power to weight is pretty atrocious, lol. Then remember its a 30 something year old car, she's pretty slow. Absolutely brilliant car though, hitting redline is always a joy in a rotary.

snippet.textDisplay: In my hunt for a well done budget sports car I went with the Fiat 124. I think it looks much better but it is also a lot easier to make power. With a simple $800 flash tune it makes over 180 whp. And that's with no correction factor added in. With a $1600 stuffed turbo kit it can make over 215 whp. An after market exhaust makes it sound like nothing a Miata can imitate. Mine has been heavily modified for racing so it handles well and is fairly quick. Yes, it is 100 pounds heavier but I'll take it. Not putting down your Miata choice. Love your channel!
